node.text:
This is the blue banded bee (Amegilla cingulate), an adorable and talented bee species found in Australia. These solitary bees use “buzz pollination” also known as sonication, a technique that is used to release pollen from certain plants that have the precious cargo firmly packed into their anthers. The blue banded bee's distinct method has even been described as "headbanging"! 🤟
​

node.text:
Meet the African spurred tortoise, Centrochelys sulcata. This little guy starts out life at just five centimeters but grows to up to 76cm in length as an adult, eventually weighing over 45kg with the heaviest reaching a whopping 90kg. Native to the southern edge of the Sahara Desert, it’s the third-largest species of tortoise in the world, and the largest species of mainland tortoise. 

The tortoise's scientific name, sulcata, comes from the Latin word sulcus, which means "furrow," and refers to the furrows on its scales. Well adapted to desert life, they can go weeks without eating or drinking, and when they do, they can guzzle up to 15% of their body weight. 

Image credit: seasoning 17 / Shutterstock.com

Happy #RedPandaDay! These adorable floofs are just a little bit bigger than a domestic cat and easily recognizable for their red coloring and thick russet fur. Red pandas (Ailurus fulgens) are also very acrobatic, being one of the only climbing species that can descend a tree head-first and rotate its ankle to control its descent.

Poaching and habitat degradation are the biggest threats to this endangered species, which has less than 10,000 individuals in the wild. Over the last 50 years, it is projected that the population has decreased by 40%.

node.text:
A necropsy reveals the "fingers" hiding beneath whales' flippers!
​
​Looking at a modern whale, it’s hard to imagine these creatures once walked on land. Of course, back then they looked a little different, but as a recent photo from a necropsy revealed, whales have hung on to a few of their land-based traits, including a rather haunting hand-like appendage. Beneath a whales’ flipper isn’t the paddle-like anatomy you might imagine, but instead a pentadactyl limb consisting of five finger-like bony protrusions.
​
The photo was posted to Twitter by Curator of Herpetology and Assistant Professor of Vertebrate Zoology at the Natural History Museum of Denmark, Dr Mark D Scherz. ​
​
​“The day before my first day, I got a message from the Collections Manager for Herpetology and Mammalogy, Daniel Klingberg Johansson, that a whale had washed up and would be dissected the following day,” Scherz told IFLScience. “These rare events spark a frenzy of activity in the museum, as various researchers and assistants work together to prepare and take data on the animal."
​
​The pentadactyl limb is actually present in an enormous variety of animals, demonstrating that they shared a common ancestor who evolved to have the limb before it went off and explored some customizations. The whales’ freaky “fingers” are therefore actually a rather beautiful demonstration of the quirks of evolution.
​
​Image courtesy of Dr Mark D. Scherz

This week, NASA confirmed that Arabia Terra, an area of northern Mars, was once the site of immense volcanic activity as thousands of “super eruptions” exploded over a period of 500 million years.

The basins left in their wake were previously thought to have been depressions left by asteroid strikes to the Martian surface. However, it now appears that they are the scars of volcanic explosions which tore through the Martian surface around 4 billion years ago.

Image credit: NASA/JPL-Caltech/University of Arizona

Because queens come in all shapes and sizes, a dazzling soldier fly has been named after RuPaul. Opaluma rupaul was crowned so in honor of its "costume of shiny metallic rainbow colours" resembling drag costumes and the "charisma and uniqueness" that lights up the bug community.

Dr. Bryan Lessard of Australia's National Research Collections hopes the news will shine a spotlight on Australia’s insect diversity, particularly those species affected by the Black Summer bushfires in 2019 and 2020.

“Many of the thirteen new soldier flies I named are from areas impacted by the Black Summer bushfires,” Dr Lessard said. “Soldier flies are valuable in the ecosystem. The larvae recycle nutrients from dead plants and animals, while adults are pollinators of some Australian plants.”

Sashay away, O rupaul.
​
​Image credit: Bryan Lessard, CSIRO

The climate crisis is unfolding around us with extreme weather events becoming more common and living organisms having to survive or perish in a changing world. In this episode, host Dr Alfredo Carpineti sat down with Dr Alexandre Kōberle, a research fellow at the Grantham Institute for Climate Change, to discuss how we got here, how we can avoid the worse case scenarios, what political will is needed, and if there are ways to actually fix the mess we are in?

Happy #OzoneDay! Today we raise awareness of the critical role of the ozone layer in our survival on planet Earth. It makes the planet inhabitable by forming a thin gaseous shield around the globe that protects it from the Sun's harmful rays.

The day is used to remind governments, corporations and individuals to do their part to maintain the ozone in opting for lower-emission and carbon neutral technologies, as well as making every day changes to reduce our negative influence on its stability. 

In 2021, the hole that emerges in Earth's ozone layer annually has been found to be unusually large, encompassing an area larger than Antarctica, according to the Copernicus Atmosphere Monitoring Service (CAMS).

Using satellite and in situ observations, researchers at CAMS have found that the hole in the ozone layer above the South Pole has grown considerably in the last fortnight after a sluggish start to the season and is now larger than 75 percent of ozone holes at this time of the year since 1979.

Hit the image post via the link in our bio to read the full story 📖
